ce:section.ce:para:
The full width at half maximum (FWHM) for each sample was measured as a parameter to more accurately estimate the depth of blood spreading within the sponges. The FWHM was calculated by averaging the brightness of each XY-slice along the Z-direction in a 3D image and fitting the best Gaussian function to it. The FWHM results are shown in front of each 3D image in Fig. 8 a–d [
49
]. The FWHM values were averaged across three repetitions of the test to ensure accuracy and calculate the error (Fig. 8 e). The average FWHM for the CMC/CS sample was one, which meant the blood had the minimum spread into the depth of this sponge. The FWHM of samples is increased by adding the CD concentration in sponges, indicating an intensified ability to absorb blood with higher CD concentration. The contact angle test showed that the CMC/CS/CD sponges had a more hydrophilic surface, which could facilitate the penetration and diffusion of blood in them. In Fig. 8 f, the intensity of pixels for all samples was summed up. All samples had equal blood volume, so the integrated intensities were almost identical. The photoacoustic signal was decreased due to light scattering in the depth of sponges; the blood penetrated into CMC/CS/CD samples, unlike CMC/CS samples, and resulted in a slight reduction of the integrated intensity of CMC/CS samples [50].
